 [[UHF]] ([[Hanthana]])\n| terr chan 4       = Channel 22\n| terr serv 5       = [[UHF]] ([[Matugama]])\n| terr chan 5       = Channel 40\n| terr serv 6       = [[UHF]] ([[Gongala]])\n| terr chan 6       = Channel 37\n| terr serv 7       = [[UHF]] ([[Gammaduwa]])\n| terr chan 7       = Channel 37\n| terr serv 8       = [[UHF]] ([[Kikiliyamana]])\n| terr chan 8       = Channel 33\n| terr serv 9       = [[UHF]] ([[Ratnapura]])\n| terr chan 9       = Channel 22\n| terr serv 10      = TV Lanka Digital TV \n| terr chan 10      = Channel 8 \n| sat serv 1        = [[Dialog TV]]\n| sat chan 1        = Channel 7\n| sat serv 2        = [[Dish TV (Sri Lanka)|Dish TV]]\n| sat chan 2        = Channel 2516\n| cable serv 1      = [[Ask Cable Vision]]\n| cable chan 1      = Channel 6\n| iptv serv 1       = [[PEO TV]]\n| iptv chan 1       = Channel 6\n| online serv 1     =\n| online chan 1     = \n}}\n'''Swarnavahini''' ({{lang-si|\u0dc3\u0dca\u0dc0\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dab\u0dc0\u0dcf\u0dc4\u0dd2\u0db1\u0dd3}}; literally Golden Channel) is a [[Sinhala language]] general entertainment and news television channel in [[Sri Lanka]] owned by [[EAP Broadcasting Company]], a subsidiary of [[EAP Holdings]]. Launched in 1994 as '''ETV''' (Extra Terrestrial Vision), it was one of Sri Lanka's first privately owned television channels.<ref name=PR>{{cite web|title=Sri Lanka|url=http://www.pressreference.com/Sa-Sw/Sri-Lanka.html|publisher=Press Reference}}</ref> Its sister channel [[ETV 2 (Sri Lanka)|ETV 2]] was launched in 1995 when ETV was re-branded ETV 1.<ref name=PR/> The channel's owner Extra Terrestrial Vision (Private) Limited, who had been incorporated on 6 July 1992, changed its name to EAP Network (Private) Limited on 30 April 1996 following the acquisition by EAP.<ref name=CSE4>{{cite web|title=EAP Broadcasting Company Limited: Debenture Issue 2015|url=https://www.cse.lk/pdf/EAP_Pros1.pdf|publisher=[[Colombo Stock Exchange]]|page=4}}</ref> At that time ETV 1 was re-broadcasting [[BBC]].<ref name=CSE39>{{cite web|title=EAP Broadcasting Company Limited: Debenture Issue 2015|url=https://www.cse.lk/pdf/EAP_Pros1.pdf|publisher=[[Colombo Stock Exchange]]|page=39}}</ref> ETV 1 was re-launched as Swarnavahini, a mass market Sinhala language channel, on 16 March 1997.<ref name=CSE39/><ref>{{cite web|title=EAP Broadcasting Company Limited: Debenture Issue 2015|url=https://www.cse.lk/pdf/EAP_Pros1.pdf|publisher=[[Colombo Stock Exchange]]|page=38}}</ref> EAP Network (Private) Limited changed its name to EAP Broadcasting Company (Private) Limited on 16 May 2012, EAP Network (Private) Limited on 31 October 2012, EAP Network Limited on 28 August 2013 and EAP Broadcasting Company Limited on 11 September 2013.<ref name=CSE4/>\n\nSwarnavahini is available on [[free-to-air]] on analogue terrestrial transmission via UHF channels 35/40 in the [[Badulla]] area, UHF channel 31 in the [[Colombo]] area, UHF channels 22/40 in the [[Kandy]] area, UHF channel 37 in the [[Matale]] area, UHF channel 37 in the [[Matara, Sri Lanka|Matara]] area, UHF channel 33 in the [[Nuwara Eliya]] area and UHF channel 22 in the [[Ratnapura]] area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiawaves.net/sri-lanka-tv.htm|title=Television Stations in Sri Lanka|author=Alan G. Davies|date=21 February 2010}}</ref> It is available via satellite on [[Dialog TV]] (channel 7) and [[Dish TV (Sri Lanka)|Dish TV]] (channel 2516).<ref>{{cite web|title=Channels|url=https://www.dialog.lk/browse/tvChannels.jsp?categoryId=onlinecat3440064|publisher=[[Dialog TV]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=List of Channels on Dialog TV|url=http://www.tvchannellists.com/List_of_Channels_on_Dialog_TV|publisher=TV Channels List}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Packs: Ntertainment|url=http://www.dishtv.lk/ntertainment.html|publisher=[[Dish TV (Sri Lanka)]]}}</ref> It is also available on Lanka Broadband Networks cable TV and [[PEO TV]] IPTV (channel 6).<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Channels|url=http://www.lbn.lk/channels.html|publisher=Lanka Broadband Networks|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320230611/http://www.lbn.lk/channels.html|archivedate=20 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Channel Lineup|url=http://www.peotv.com/?p=channel_lineup|publisher=PEO TV}}</ref>\n\nThe popular news reading program ''Mul Pituwa'' presented by journalist Bandula Padmakumara successfully aired its 1000th program on 30 March 2006.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/060326/tv/9.html | title=\u2018Mul Pituwa\u2019 reaches milestone | publisher=Sunday Times | accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Teledramas==\n*''Hadawathe Kathawa''\n*''Dangale''\n*''Aeya''\n*''No Parking''\n\n===Finished Teledramas===\n*''Queen''\n*''Kumi''\n*[[Haara Kotiya|Kotipathiyo]]\n*''Wes''\n*''Sakuge Kathawa''\n*''Sillara Samanallu''\n*''Anantha''\n*''Monara Kadadasi''\n*''Package''\n*''Saki'' \n*''Click''\n*''Thawa Durai Jeewithe''\n*''See Raja''\n*''Ran Bedi Minissu''\n*''Daskon''\n\n===Dubbed Teledramas===\n*[[Aladdin - Naam Toh Suna Hoga]] as ''Aladdin''\n*[[Paramavatar Shri Krishna]] as ''Maharaja Kansa''\n*[[Chandra Nandini]] as ''Chandra Nandani''\n*[[Tamanna (TV series)|Tamanna]] as ''Dhara''\n*[[Saath Nibhaana Saathiya]] as ''Mage Sanda Obai''\n*[[Mahabharat (2013 TV series)|Mahabharat]] as ''Mahabharat''\n*[[Shaka Laka Boom Boom]] as ''Maya Pensala''\n\n\n'''<big>Cartoons</big>'''\n\n* \u0dc3\u0dd2\u0dbd\u0dca\u0dc0\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dca\n* \u0dc3\u0dd9\u0db1\u0dca\u0db4\u0dad\u0dd2 \u0d85\u0da9\u0dc0\u0dd2\u0dba\n* \u0dbb\u0ddd\u0dc3\u0dd2 \u0d86\u0da0\u0dca\u0da0\u0dd2\n* Ghost Busters\n\n<br />\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Url|swarnavahini.lk}}\n* [http://www.sundaytimes.lk/070923/TV/tv-times00001.html Family Doctor to cure tele diseases]\n* [http://www.sundaytimes.lk/100808/Magazine/sundaytimestvtimes_3.html Dance Stars Dance on Swarnavahini]\n\n{{Media of Sri Lanka}}\n\n[[Category:1994 establishments in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:EAP Networks]]\n[[Category:Sinhala-language television sta