{"title_page": "Esther Wojcicki", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Dr. Esther Wojcicki\n| image              = Esther Wojcicki (cropped).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Wojcicki in June 2008\n| birth_name         = Esther Denise Hochman\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1940|5|26}}\n| birth_place        = New York City\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = American\n| alma_mater         = [[University of California, Berkeley|UC Berkeley]]<br/>[[University of Paris]]<br/>[[San Jose State University]]\n| occupation         = Journalist, educator\n| known_for          = Moonshots: The Woj Way Pedagogical Philosophy (Trust Framework)\n| spouse             = [[Stanley Wojcicki]]\n| children           = [[Susan Wojcicki]]<br/> Janet Wojcicki<br/> [[Anne Wojcicki]]\n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n}}\n\n'''Esther Denise''' \"'''Woj'''\" '''Hochman Wojcicki'''<ref name=bookref1>{{cite book|title=Who's who in the West: A Biographical Dictionary of Noteworthy Men and Women of the Pacific Coast and the Western States|date=2004|publisher=A.N. Marquis Company|isbn=9780837909356|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZZxmAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2015-04-16}}</ref> ({{IPAc-en|w|\u028a|\u02c8|t\u0283|\u026a|t|s|k|i}} {{respell|wuu|CHITS|kee}})<ref>{{YouTube|enZHpoaRljE|\"Esther Wojcicki - Empowering Students\"}}</ref> is an American [[journalist]], [[educator]],<ref name=\"cc press release\">{{cite web|url=https://creativecommons.org/press-releases/entry/8469|title=Education Innovator Esther Wojcicki Joins Creative Commons Board|last=Hwang|first=Tim|date=2008-07-10|publisher=Creative Commons|accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref><ref name=\"curriki\">{{cite web|url=http://www.curriki.org/xwiki/bin/view/Advisory/Wojcicki|title=Curriki -  Wojcicki|accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref> and vice chair of the [[Creative Commons]] advisory council.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://creativecommons.org/about/team/ |title=Board of Directors - Creative Commons |publisher= Creative Commons |accessdate= 2010-12-05}}</ref> Wojcicki has studied education and [[technology]].<ref name=\"cc press release\"/> She is the founder of the Palo Alto High School Media Arts Program in Palo Alto, CA.<ref>{{Citation|last=Esther Wojcicki|title=Journalism and the Common Core Writing Standards|date=2013-06-09|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iyaOyNZV3aE|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nWojcicki is the oldest of three children, and was the first in her family to attend college. Her parents were [[History of the Jews in Russia|Russian Jewish]] immigrants who came to [[New York City]] in the 1930s. Her family moved to Southern California after she was born.<ref name=\"palo alto online\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jwa.org/blog/esther-wojcicki-jewish-mother-of-tech-revolution |website=Jewish Woman's Archives|title= Esther Wojcicki: A Jewish mother of the tech revolution|first= Preeva |last=Tramiel|date= April 18, 2012}}</ref> Wojcicki was [[valedictorian]] of her high school class,<ref name=\"palo alto online\">{{cite web|url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/weekly/morgue/news/1998_Apr_29.PEOPLE29.html|title=People: Esther Wojcicki: Carrying the torch for free speech |last=Lorenz|first=Elizabeth|date=1998-04-29|publisher=Palo Alto Online|accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref> and graduated from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] with a B.A. in English and [[Political Science]]. She received a secondary teaching credential from University of California, Berkeley, as well as a graduate degree from the Graduate School of Journalism at Berkeley. She has an advanced degree in [[French language|French]] and [[French History]] from the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]], and both a Secondary School Administrative Credential and a M.A. in [[Educational Technology]] from [[San Jose State University]].<ref name=\"cc press release\"/><ref name=\"curriki\"/>\n\n==Career==\nWojcicki has taught at [[Palo Alto High School]] since 1984, where she currently teaches [[journalism]] and [[English language|English]]. There she began the journalism program which has grown to become one of the largest in America.<ref name=\"huffington post bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/esther-wojcicki#|title=Esther Wojcicki|publisher=HuffingtonPost.com, Inc|accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref> She has worked as a professional journalist for multiple publications and blogs regularly for [[The Huffington Post]].<ref name=\"cc press release\"/>\n\nWojcicki was the 1990 Northern California Journalism teacher of the year,<ref name=\"cc press release\"/> and was selected as the California Teacher of the Year in 2002 by the [[California Commission on Teacher Credentialing]].<ref name=\"huffington post bio\"/> She served on the University of California Office of the President Curriculum Committee where she helped revise the beginning and advanced journalism curriculum for the state of California.<ref name=\"curriki\"/> In 2009, she was awarded the Gold Key by Columbia Scholastic Press Association in recognition of outstanding devotion to the cause of the school press.<ref name=\"gold key\">{{cite web|url=http://cspa.columbia.edu/docs/spr/current-issue/04-Wojcicki-Key/index.html|title=Esther Wojcicki receives Gold Key|publisher=Columbia Scholastic Press Association|accessdate=2009-05-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615075514/http://cspa.columbia.edu/docs/spr/current-issue/04-Wojcicki-Key/index.html|archive-date=2009-06-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Wojcicki is also on the Board of Trustees of the \"Developmental Studies Center\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devstu.org/page/board-of-trustees|title=Board of Trustees|website=devstu.org}}</ref> and on the Board of Governors of the \"Alliance for Excellent Education\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130329033852/http://www.all4ed.org/about_the_alliance/leadership/Governing+Board|title=Governing Board {{!}} Alliance for Excellent Education|date=2013-03-29|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> She serves as Chairman of the Board of \"Learning Matters\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://learningmatters.tv/|title=Education Week Video|website=learningmatters.tv}}</ref> and is part of the Advisory Board at the THNK School of Creative Leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thnk.org/|title=Innovation & Creativity Development- THNK School of Creative Leadership|website=THNK}}</ref> She is Chief Learning Officer for Explore<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.exploreplanet3.com|title=Home|website=Planet3|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> Planet3, an exploration based science platform for middle school students. She is on the board of the Newseum in Washington, D.C and the Freedom Forum. She holds an honorary doctorate from Palo Alto University (2013) and from Rhode Island School of Design (2016). She is  the founder of the Journalistic Learning Initiative at the University of Oregon School of Communications and School of Education (2016) www.journalisticlearning.com. She is the founder of the Moonshots in Education Movement (MiE) that can be found at www.Moonshots.org.(2017). In 2019 she was the author of the book \"How to Raise Successful People<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raisesuccessfulpeople.com/|title=How to Raise Successful People|last=Wojcicki|first=Esther|website=How to Raise Successful People}}</ref>\", a parenting book on the philosophy she used in raising her 3 daughters. Wojcicki discussed her life and the book on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Woman's Hour]]'' in May 2019.<ref name=\"Woman's Hour\">{{cite episode| title= Small Island, Esther Wojcicki, Natalie Haynes | series= [[Woman's Hour]]| credits= Presenter: [[Jenni Murray]] | network= BBC| station= [[BBC Radio 4]]| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0004mc9| airdate= 2 May 2019| minutes= 0:47 | accessdate= 7 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\nMs. Wojcicki mentored [[Steve Jobs]]' daughter, [[Lisa Brennan-Jobs]], in High School.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/23/books/steve-jobs-lisa-brennan-jobs-small-fry.html|title=In \u2018Small Fry,\u2019 Steve Jobs Comes Across as a Jerk. His Daughter Forgives Him. Should We?|last=Bowles|first=Nellie|date=2018-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHer husband is [[Stanford University]] [[professor]] of [[physics]] [[Stanley Wojcicki]]. They have three daughters: [[Susan Wojcicki|Susan]] (CEO of [[YouTube]]), Janet, a [[Fulbright Award|Fulbright-winning]] anthropologist, Assistant Professor of Pediatrics and researcher, and [[Anne Wojcicki|Anne]] (co-founder of [[23andMe]]), and nine grandchildren.<ref name=\"huffington post bio\"/>\n\n== Works ==\n* ''How to raise successful people : simple lessons for radical results'', London : Hutchinson, 2019. {{ISBN|9781786331267}}, {{OCLC|1090425189}}\n\n/* Works */ Moonshots in Education: Launching Blended Learning in the Classroom, Pacific Research Institute, San Francisco, 2015 ISBN-13 978-1-934276-20-4\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/esther-wojcicki/ Esther Wojcicki's blog] at [[The Huffington Post]]\n*[http://www.classwish.org ClassWish.org]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wojcicki, Esther}}\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Creative Commons Board of Directors]]\n[[Category:People from Palo Alto, California]]\n[[Category:San Jose State University alumni]]\n[[Category:UC Berkeley Graduate School of Journalism alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Dr. Esther Wojcicki\n| image              = Esther Wojcicki (cropped).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Wojcicki in June 2008\n| birth_name         = Esther Denise Hochman\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1940|5|26}}\n| birth_place        = New York City\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = American\n| alma_mater         = [[University of California, Berkeley|UC Berkeley]]<br/>[[University of Paris]]<br/>[[San Jose State University]]\n| occupation         = Journalist, educator\n| known_for          = Moonshots: The Woj Way Pedagogical Philosophy (Trust Framework)\n| spouse             = [[Stanley Wojcicki]]\n| children           = [[Susan Wojcicki]]<br/> Janet Wojcicki<br/> [[Anne Wojcicki]]\n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n}}\n\n'''Esther Denise''' \"'''Woj'''\" '''Hochman Wojcicki'''<ref name=bookref1>{{cite book|title=Who's who in the West: A Biographical Dictionary of Noteworthy Men and Women of the Pacific Coast and the Western States|date=2004|publisher=A.N. Marquis Company|isbn=9780837909356|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZZxmAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2015-04-16}}</ref> ({{IPAc-en|w|\u028a|\u02c8|t\u0283|\u026a|t|s|k|i}} {{respell|wuu|CHITS|kee}})<ref>{{YouTube|enZHpoaRljE|\"Esther Wojcicki - Empowering Students\"}}</ref> is an American [[journalist]], [[educator]],<ref name=\"cc press release\">{{cite web|url=https://creativecommons.org/press-releases/entry/8469|title=Education Innovator Esther Wojcicki Joins Creative Commons Board|last=Hwang|first=Tim|date=2008-07-10|publisher=Creative Commons|accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref><ref name=\"curriki\">{{cite web|url=http://www.curriki.org/xwiki/bin/view/Advisory/Wojcicki|title=Curriki -  Wojcicki|accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref> and vice chair of the [[Creative Commons]] advisory council.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://creativecommons.org/about/team/ |title=Board of Directors - Creative Commons |publisher= Creative Commons |accessdate= 2010-12-05}}</ref> Wojcicki has studied education and [[technology]].<ref name=\"cc press release\"/> She is the founder of the Palo Alto High School Media Arts Program in Palo Alto, CA.<ref>{{Citation|last=Esther Wojcicki|title=Journalism and the Common Core Writing Standards|date=2013-06-09|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iyaOyNZV3aE|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nWojcicki is the oldest of three children, and was the first in her family to attend college. Her parents were [[History of the Jews in Russia|Russian Jewish]] immigrants who came to [[New York City]] in the 1930s. Her family moved to Southern California after she was born.<ref name=\"palo alto online\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jwa.org/blog/esther-wojcicki-jewish-mother-of-tech-revolution |website=Jewish Woman's Archives|title= Esther Wojcicki: A Jewish mother of the tech revolution|first= Preeva |last=Tramiel|date= April 18, 2012}}</ref> Wojcicki was [[valedictorian]] of her high school class,<ref name=\"palo alto online\">{{cite web|url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/weekly/morgue/news/1998_Apr_29.PEOPLE29.html|title=People: Esther Wojcicki: Carrying the torch for free speech |last=Lorenz|first=Elizabeth|date=1998-04-29|publisher=Palo Alto Online|accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref> and graduated from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] with a B.A. in English and [[Political Science]]. She received a secondary teaching credential from University of California, Berkeley, as well as a graduate degree from the Graduate School of Journalism at Berkeley. She has an advanced degree in [[French language|French]] and [[French History]] from the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]], and both a Secondary School Administrative Credential and a M.A. in [[Educational Technology]] from [[San Jose State University]].<ref name=\"cc press release\"/><ref name=\"curriki\"/>\n\n==Career==\nWojcicki has taught at [[Palo Alto High School]] since 1984, where she currently teaches [[journalism]] and [[English language|English]]. There she began the journalism program which has grown to become one of the largest in America.<ref name=\"huffington post bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/esther-wojcicki#|title=Esther Wojcicki|publisher=HuffingtonPost.com, Inc|accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref> She has worked as a professional journalist for multiple publications and blogs regularly for [[The Huffington Post]].<ref name=\"cc press release\"/>\n\nWojcicki was the 1990 Northern California Journalism teacher of the year,<ref name=\"cc press release\"/> and was selected as the California Teacher of the Year in 2002 by the [[California Commission on Teacher Credentialing]].<ref name=\"huffington post bio\"/> She served on the University of California Office of the President Curriculum Committee where she helped revise the beginning and advanced journalism curriculum for the state of California.<ref name=\"curriki\"/> In 2009, she was awarded the Gold Key by Columbia Scholastic Press Association in recognition of outstanding devotion to the cause of the school press.<ref name=\"gold key\">{{cite web|url=http://cspa.columbia.edu/docs/spr/current-issue/04-Wojcicki-Key/index.html|title=Esther Wojcicki receives Gold Key|publisher=Columbia Scholastic Press Association|accessdate=2009-05-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615075514/http://cspa.columbia.edu/docs/spr/current-issue/04-Wojcicki-Key/index.html|archive-date=2009-06-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Wojcicki is also on the Board of Trustees of the \"Developmental Studies Center\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devstu.org/page/board-of-trustees|title=Board of Trustees|website=devstu.org}}</ref> and on the Board of Governors of the \"Alliance for Excellent Education\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130329033852/http://www.all4ed.org/about_the_alliance/leadership/Governing+Board|title=Governing Board {{!}} Alliance for Excellent Education|date=2013-03-29|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> She serves as Chairman of the Board of \"Learning Matters\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://learningmatters.tv/|title=Education Week Video|website=learningmatters.tv}}</ref> and is part of the Advisory Board at the THNK School of Creative Leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thnk.org/|title=Innovation & Creativity Development- THNK School of Creative Leadership|website=THNK}}</ref> She is Chief Learning Officer for Explore<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.exploreplanet3.com|title=Home|website=Planet3|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> Planet3, an exploration based science platform for middle school students. She is on the board of the Newseum in Washington, D.C and the Freedom Forum. She holds an honorary doctorate from Palo Alto University (2013) and from Rhode Island School of Design (2016). She is  the founder of the Journalistic Learning Initiative at the University of Oregon School of Communications and School of Education (2016) www.journalisticlearning.com. She is the founder of the Moonshots in Education Movement (MiE) that can be found at www.Moonshots.org.(2017). In 2019 she was the author of the book \"How to Raise Successful People<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raisesuccessfulpeople.com/|title=How to Raise Successful People|last=Wojcicki|first=Esther|website=How to Raise Successful People}}</ref>\", a parenting book on the philosophy she used in raising her 3 daughters. Wojcicki discussed her life and the book on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Woman's Hour]]'' in May 2019.<ref name=\"Woman's Hour\">{{cite episode| title= Small Island, Esther Wojcicki, Natalie Haynes | series= [[Woman's Hour]]| credits= Presenter: [[Jenni Murray]] | network= BBC| station= [[BBC Radio 4]]| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0004mc9| airdate= 2 May 2019| minutes= 0:47 | accessdate= 7 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\nMs. Wojcicki mentored [[Steve Jobs]]' daughter, [[Lisa Brennan-Jobs]], in High School.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/23/books/steve-jobs-lisa-brennan-jobs-small-fry.html|title=In \u2018Small Fry,\u2019 Steve Jobs Comes Across as a Jerk. His Daughter Forgives Him. Should We?|last=Bowles|first=Nellie|date=2018-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHer husband is [[Stanford University]] [[professor]] of [[physics]] [[Stanley Wojcicki]]. They have three daughters: [[Susan Wojcicki|Susan]] (CEO of [[YouTube]]), Janet, a [[Fulbright Award|Fulbright-winning]] anthropologist, Assistant Professor of Pediatrics and researcher, and [[Anne Wojcicki|Anne]] (co-founder of [[23andMe]]), and nine grandchildren.<ref name=\"huffington post bio\"/>\n\n== Works ==\n* ''How to raise successful people : simple lessons for radical results'', London : Hutchinson, 2019. {{ISBN|9781786331267}}, {{OCLC|1090425189}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/esther-wojcicki/ Esther Wojcicki's blog] at [[The Huffington Post]]\n*[http://www.classwish.org ClassWish.org]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wojcicki, Esther}}\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Creative Commons Board of Directors]]\n[[Category:People from Palo Alto, California]]\n[[Category:San Jose State University alumni]]\n[[Category:UC Berkeley Graduate School of Journalism alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n", "name_user": "EstherWoj", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esther_Wojcicki"}
